Mary Lou Woods, assistant vice president and associate treasurer of Pomona, said that rising expectations for school services drove increased spending.

“The expectations of what the world wants us to provide continue to rise,” Woods said. “As students and families are weighing their options of different institutions, they’re \[asking\], is there a health and wellness center? Is there a rock climbing wall? There is a desire to have a very hands on student affairs \[and support in addition to\] the instruction side.”

Rachael Warecki, a spokesperson for Scripps, pointed to increased co-curricular spending as one reason for increasing expenses.

“Costs related to the addition of a new Residence Hall, together with major renovations to several other Residence Halls, including the addition of air conditioning and addressing ADA accessibility, was a major driver of costs in co-curricular expenditures for \[Scripps\] College over recent years,” she said.

[div style:`{margin: "48px 0"}`]

![Photo of Toll Hall, a residence hall at Scripps College](https://tsl.news/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Matejka_Scripps-Colonial1-1500x1000.jpg)

[p style:`{fontSize: 16}`]Residence hall renovations were major contributors to expenditure increases at Scripps, according to Warecki. (Janey Matejka • The Student Life)[/p]

[/div]

Academic and institutional support expenses have also increased.

According to Rob Goldberg, Pomona Chief Operating Officer and Treasurer, part of the increase stems from the need to provide competitive salaries.

“Over 50 percent of our budget covers salaries and benefits for our faculty and staff, and each year we increase compensation to keep up with higher costs of living and to recruit and attract the best faculty and staff we can,” he said in an email.

Judy Augsburger, a spokesperson for Harvey Mudd, said that a [2013 ten-year growth plan](https://www.hmc.edu/growth/) was a key reason for the steepness of the college’s tuition increases since 2011-12. The plan called for increasing faculty, staff and facility resources to accommodate 900 students by 2023. Harvey Mudd [had 902 full-time undergraduate students](https://www.hmc.edu/institutional-research/institutional-statistics/institutional-statistics-students/student-enrollment/) in 2021-22, up from 777 in 2011-12.

Broadly, “people, insurance, food and utilities” were responsible for the greatest increases in Pitzer's expenses, spokesperson Wendy Shattuck said via email.

